		<b>Comment By Jenny Shank, 9-07-05</b>
		<p>I haven't read it yet, but that book is by Heidi Julavits, who set the book in Pueblo because her grandmother lived in that town for two years during the depression.  There's kind of a funny story about this, too: Julavits, who has never lived in Colorado, changed a few details about Pueblo in the novel, such as turning it into a mining town, and met with protests from Pueblo residents when she did a reading in Colorado.  (Probably because Colorado is so often ignored by New York publishers that on the rare occasion when a major publisher puts out a book of literary fiction set in Colorado, people are eager to see themselves and their home state accurately portrayed.) Julavits wrote an article about this experience and why she thinks fiction writers should have the right to stretch the truth for <i>Poets & Writers</i>in the 2002 January/February issue. It was called "Fiction 21c: History as an Occasion for Literature," but unfortunately it's not online any more.<br />
<br />
The site does offer the rebuttal a reader wrote to her article, though:<br />
<a href="http://www.newwest.net/?URL=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.pw.org%2Fmag%2Fletters0203.htm">http://www.pw.org/mag/letters0203.htm</a></p>
		
		<b>Comment By Tom Miller, 9-16-05</b>
		<p>Literary maps draw in a wide range of readers and make excellent placemats and conversation starters. Years ago a company brought out poster-sized literary maps of Central and South America, though no one I know seems to still have one. For my recent book, "Writing on the Edge: A Borderlands Reader" (University of Arizona Press), I drew on some of the best writing about the U.S.-Mexico frontier from the last hundred years to show what a vibrant literary turf the borderlands encapsules – on both sides. It includes short stories, essays, corridos, travelogues, poetry, cuentos, a couple of cartoons, crónicas, and even a short play. The authors range from Graham Greene to Flaco Jiménez.  Because the book was by necessity linear, we wanted to spice it up with a map that linked each contributor to a geographic place. Cartographic precision was not our primary concern; nobody was going to drive anywhere or measure distance by this map. Still, we wanted each of the 80-some authors to be represented, those from the U.S. and Mexican as well. For our artist, we chose Diane Sylvain, who draws those slightly goofy maps for High Country News. The result was a reasonably accurate and wildly stylized double-truck map of The Literary Borderland. We’re very proud of it. You can see it on pp. xxii and xxiii of "Writing on the Edge."<br />
<br />
And a very nice P.S.: New Times, Inc., the parent company of alternative weeklies throughout the country, underwrote production of a printing of the map, enlarged on placemat-sized quality bond paper. We used it for promotion – book stores, colleges, etc. – and I bring a fistful to the occasional talk about the border I give here and there.</p>
		
		<b>Comment By secondtear, 10-31-05</b>
